---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Quantization Insights" activePage="quantization" description="AesSedai vs Unsloth quant comparison, MXFP4 notes, and Qwen3.5 architecture observations">
  <div class="page-header fade-up">
    <h1>Quantization Insights</h1>
    <p class="description">Empirical findings on quantization methods, quant provider comparisons, and architecture-specific behaviors discovered through benchmarking.</p>
  </div>

  <h2>AesSedai vs Unsloth (Qwen3.5 MoE)</h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>For Qwen3.5 MoE models (35B-A3B, 122B-A10B), we tested quants from both <strong>AesSedai</strong> (MoE-aware quantization) and <strong>Unsloth</strong> (Dynamic 2.0). The differences are significant and measurable.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Metric</th>
          <th>AesSedai Q4_K_M</th>
          <th>Unsloth UD-Q4_K_XL (fixed)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Strategy</td><td>Protects attention/shared experts at Q8_0, differentiates ffn_down from ffn_gate/up</td><td>Dynamic 2.0 &mdash; upcasts critical layers, new imatrix (Mar 5)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">35B-A3B pp (RADV)</td><td class="best">832 t/s</td><td>795 t/s</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">35B-A3B tg (AMDVLK)</td><td class="best">53 t/s</td><td>48 t/s</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">35B-A3B Coding</td><td class="best">10/10 (158s)</td><td>10/10 (228s)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">35B-A3B Creative Writing</td><td class="best">~25-26/30</td><td>~24/30</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">35B-A3B Size</td><td>21 GiB</td><td class="best">19 GiB</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">122B-A10B pp (RADV)</td><td>259 t/s</td><td>258 t/s</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">122B-A10B Coding</td><td>10/10 (415s)</td><td>10/10 (517s)</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">122B-A10B Creative Writing</td><td>~28/30</td><td>~28/30</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="insight success fade-up">
    <p><strong>AesSedai wins on 35B speed and quality.</strong> 30-45% faster pp, ~10% faster tg on 35B. For 122B, the gap is nearly closed: identical performance (258 vs 259 pp), same coding score, and Unsloth actually has fewer prose style violations (5 vs 19 colons).</p>
  </div>

  <h3>The Unsloth MXFP4 Bug</h3>
  <div class="insight danger fade-up">
    <p><strong>Critical bug found and fixed (2026-02-27):</strong> Unsloth's UD-Q4_K_XL was applying MXFP4 quantization to attention tensors by mistake. This caused coding to drop from 10/10 to 8/10 (TTL bugs from corrupted attention weights). The fix restored coding to 10/10 but creative writing quality remained slightly below AesSedai (~24 vs ~25-26/30).</p>
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2>MXFP4: QAT vs Post-Hoc</h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>MXFP4 (Microscaling FP4) quantization behaves very differently depending on how it was applied:</p>
  </div>

  <div class="stats-grid fade-up">
    <div class="card">
      <h3>QAT-Trained MXFP4</h3>
      <p>Models trained with quantization-aware training (like GPT-OSS-120B) <strong>outperform standard quants</strong>. The model learned to compensate for reduced precision during training.</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-muted);">GPT-OSS-120B MXFP4: 661 pp, 53 tg &mdash; excellent for 59 GiB</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h3>Post-Hoc MXFP4</h3>
      <p>Applying MXFP4 to a BF16 model after training <strong>underperforms standard quants</strong> like Q4_K_M. The precision loss isn't compensated for.</p>
      <p style="font-size: 0.85rem; color: var(--text-muted);">Bad for Qwen3.5 MoE &mdash; corrupted attention weights before fix</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2>Qwen3.5 Dense Architecture Bottleneck</h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>Qwen3.5 dense models (4B, 9B, 27B) exhibit a <strong>token generation speed bottleneck</strong> that is consistent across all backends and quants. This appears to be an architecture-level issue, not related to quantization or driver choice.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Model</th>
          <th>Size</th>
          <th>tg (RADV)</th>
          <th>tg (AMDVLK)</th>
          <th>tg (ROCm)</th>
          <th>Expected tg</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Qwen3.5-4B Q8_0</td><td>4 GiB</td><td>37.9</td><td class="best">40.0</td><td>36.3</td><td>~80+</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Qwen3.5-9B Q8_0</td><td>9 GiB</td><td>22.5</td><td class="best">23.3</td><td>22.3</td><td>~60+</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="model-name">Qwen3.5-27B UD-Q4_K_XL</td><td>16 GiB</td><td>11.35</td><td class="best">11.90</td><td>11.28</td><td>~40+</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="insight warning fade-up">
    <p><strong>The tg speeds barely vary across backends</strong> &mdash; typically within 1-2 t/s of each other. Compare to Qwen3-30B (MoE) which gets 75 t/s on RADV at a similar model size. The bottleneck appears to be in how the dense Qwen3.5 architecture interacts with the inference engine, not in compute throughput.</p>
  </div>

  <h3>Impact on Usability</h3>
  <ul class="findings fade-up">
    <li><strong>27B is impractical</strong> at 6-11 t/s &mdash; too slow for interactive use. Also fails coding (0/10, thinking consumes all tokens).</li>
    <li><strong>9B is usable</strong> at 22-23 t/s &mdash; acceptable for generation tasks, 10/10 coding in no-think mode.</li>
    <li><strong>4B is surprisingly capable</strong> at 38-40 t/s &mdash; good for lightweight tasks, 9/10 coding.</li>
    <li><strong>pp is not bottlenecked</strong> &mdash; Qwen3.5-4B hits 1375 pp on RADV, showing the issue is tg-specific.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="divider"></div>

  <h2>Qwen3.5-35B-A3B Prose Loop</h2>
  <div class="card fade-up">
    <p>A persistent issue with Qwen3.5-35B-A3B: the model enters a repetition loop during long-form prose generation, producing 19,000-21,000 words instead of the target 2,900. This happens on <strong>every quant tested</strong>:</p>
  </div>

  <div class="table-wrap fade-up">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Quant Tested</th>
          <th>Provider</th>
          <th>Loop?</th>
          <th>Words</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Q8_0</td><td>Standard</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~21k</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q5_K_M</td><td>Standard</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~20k</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q4_K_M</td><td>AesSedai</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~21k</td></tr>
        <tr><td>UD-Q4_K_XL (old)</td><td>Unsloth</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~20k</td></tr>
        <tr><td>UD-Q4_K_XL (fixed)</td><td>Unsloth</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~19.5k</td></tr>
        <tr><td>MXFP4_MOE</td><td>Unsloth</td><td class="badge failed">Yes</td><td>~20k</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <div class="insight fade-up">
    <p><strong>This is an architecture/stop-condition issue</strong>, not quant-dependent. The short story bench (shorter output) completes cleanly on all quants. The prose bench's longer output requirement triggers degeneration. Notably, the larger Qwen3.5-122B-A10B had the same issue but it was <strong>fixed in llama.cpp b8182</strong> (likely the M-RoPE kv-cache shift fix).</p>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
